2.1. Core Components
Before delving into the detailed components of large language models (LLMs), it is necessary to understand how these models process input data. The first step is breaking down the raw text into smaller units called tokens, which serve as the fundamental building blocks for the model’s understanding. These tokens are then transformed and processed through a series of layers and mechanisms. They include embeddings, attention modules, and feed-forward networks. They enable the model to learn complex language patterns and generate meaningful output.
• Tokenization: The starting point is to divide input text into smaller units called tokens. Tokens can be characters, words, or subwords depending on the used model and tokenizer. This enables the LLM to structure the input data and learn patterns. As a result, LLMs can produce well-structured and coherent language output [20]. • Embedding Layer: The next step consists of translating each word into a set of numbers that models their meanings. In this way, words with similar significances will have the same numerical representations. Different mechanisms are used to ensure words embeddings such as GloVe [21] and Word2Vec [22]. Transformers use positional embeddings to identify the position of each word in the sentence. • Transformer Architecture: The transformer architecture consists of both multi-head attention and self-attention. • Self-Attention Mechanism: This mechanism is a core module of the transformer architecture [23]. It helps the model to evaluate the importance of each word when processing data. LLMs can focus on pertinent words despite of their position when generating output text. • Feed Forward Network: A feed-forward network (FFN) is the second part of the transformer model [24]. It deals with each input token separately. A feed-forward network is composed of two layers of neurons that refine learned information. It helps the model to update each token’s representation based on self-attention mechanism results.
All these blocs allow LLM models to efficiently manage and understand language by extracting the meaning and the order of expressions. Consequently, they will perform all tasks from text generation, summarization, to translation. The Figure 1 illustrates the main components involved in this process.
2.2. Examples of LLMs
LLMs evolved rapidly with different objectives, applications, and various architectures. We previously described some models such as GPT, PALM, and LLAMA. This section presents a deeper presentation of the most common models. We examine their usage, design and capabilities. The objective is to highlight their impact and how they are designed.
2.2.1. GPT (OpenAI)
The generative pre-trained transformer (GPT) was proposed by OpenAI. Each new version such as GPT-3, GPT-4 corresponds to new capabilities for analyzing text and reasoning [25]. The training of GPT models is divided into two steps. During the first step, models are trained using a huge amount of data. Next, models are fine tuned for specific domains. The architecture of GPT is built using the transformer decoder stack. GPT is based on 12 layers in version 2 and up to 96 for version 4. The key components of GPT repeat over these layers as follows:
• Input Embedding Layer:
– Each token is linked to a vector representation.


